    "comprehension": null,
    "direction": null,
    "content": "<p>A particle is moving uniformly along a straight line as shown in the figure. During the motion of the particle from $$A$$ to $$B$$, the angular momentum of the particle about $$O$$</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1ltr7t4lt/4217ef2c-29fd-44f6-b0d8-7244da4c20c0/97685010-e1ff-11ee-b458-0b46f9ad1420/file-1ltr7t4lu.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1ltr7t4lt/4217ef2c-29fd-44f6-b0d8-7244da4c20c0/97685010-e1ff-11ee-b458-0b46f9ad1420/file-1ltr7t4lu.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"KCET 2019 Physics - Rotational Motion Question 5 English\"></p>",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "increase"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "decrease"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "remains constant"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "first increase then decrease"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "C"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "<p>The angular momentum of a particle moving uniformly along a straight line about a point $ O $ can be analyzed through the concept of cross product $ \\mathbf{L} = \\mathbf{r} \\times \\mathbf{p} $, where $ \\mathbf{L} $ is the angular momentum, $ \\mathbf{r} $ is the position vector from the point $ O $ to the particle, and $ \\mathbf{p} $ is the linear momentum of the particle.</p>\n<p>Given the uniform motion along the line from $ A $ to $ B $:</p>\n<p>Since the direction and magnitude of the motion remain constant,</p>\n\n<p><p>As the particle moves from $ A $ to $ B $, its distance from point $ O $ changes.</p></p>\n<p><p>If the distance between $ O $ and the line of motion is constant, then the perpendicular distance from $ O $ to the particle's line of motion remains the same, keeping the angular momentum constant.</p></p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the angular momentum of the particle about point $ O $ during its motion from $ A $ to $ B $ remains constant.</p>\n<p><strong>Option C: remains constant</strong></p>",
    "topic": "angular-momentum-conservation",
